nsitively exploring issues of race and genocide that surround this controversy. Basing his discussion on vivid ethnographical data collected in the townships of Johannesburg, he passionately demonstrates that the unprecedented epidemiological crisis in South Africa is a demographic catastrophe as well as a human tragedy, one that cannot be understood without reference to the social history of the country, in particular to institutionalized racial inequality as the fundamental principle of government during the past century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAIDS (Disease)xGovernment policyzSouth Africa. 0aAIDS (Disease)xPolitical aspectszSouth Africa. 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectszSouth Africa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aaids epidemic.  aaids.  aanc government.  aanthropology.  aapartheid.  acolonial period.  acolonialism.  ademographic studies.  adissidents.  aepidemiology.  aethnography.  agenocide.  aglobal aids crisis.  aglobal controversy.  agovernment and governing.  ahealth.  ahiv.  ahuman tragedy.  ajohannesburg.  amedical anthropology.  amedical research.  amedical.  amother to child transmission.  apolitical.  apolitics.  apresident thabo mbeki.  aquestionable medical research.  arace theory.  aracial inequality.  asocial history.  asouth africa.  asouth african history.  aviral theory.1 aF., D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024467240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094045140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940451423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940451/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University 